<br>
Now, I play a druid, and often I was upset at the fact that I didn't really have 1 job to do, I just sort of filled in spots here and there since everyone does things better.....but then the other day I was grouped with a person, who for the first time found that he couldn't do his job....the mobs where resistant to him at level 60....and what happened?  Well he got depressed because he was so used to having to do one thing that he felt useless, even though he had other things he could do.  At that point in time I realize that I had learned a good lesson.....sure I may not be the best at anything but I had learned to make myself useful at all times.  There are raids where I am not allowed to DoT my nukes hit for next to nothing or are resisted...the clerics don't need my heals...but I still have some buffs, some heals, a DS and maybe they aren't the best or most effective use of my abilities but they are better then nothing.<br>
<br>
I don't know what the answers are to the caster balancing, I do know that it can be hard when you sit in one seat and look at the others and I do know that until I level those other classes up the hard way I really won't know what their problems are.  <br>
<br>
The best players learn to do the best they can with the skills they have.  I've learned which spells of mine have insane agro and used them when needed....I've managed to keep agro casting 1 tiny spell and let the thing chase me while a level 60 epic equiped rogue does all the damage killing it....and sometimes that kind of agro will save an enchanters life (and maybe splat me).  There are things that need to be done, I won't persume to say what each class needs or doesn't need....I just know that DD isn't always the best way to make your contribution count and I won't ask that my class gets improved by sacrificing another class, we're all valuable....All I do wish is that when all is said and done we all feel a bit better about who we are.<br>
<br>
<br>
Keryia<br>
